		<!-- Marginalia -->
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						Volo Musam cantantem, Saltantem, currentem, "
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						" equitatantem, nauigantem, circumuolitante[m];
						
						Luctantem,
						gladiantem; pra[e]liantem, fulminantem; tonantem;
						omnia egregia facinora perpetrantem.
						Da mihi hanc Musam: aut sperno.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>I want a singing, dancing, running, riding, sailing, flying-around; wrestling, fighting, battling, lightning-hurling, and thundering Muse who accomplishes all extraordinary deeds.
			Give me this Muse: or I scorn.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sententia[e] de rupe adamantis. dicta Solis <!--JG: Should be rupe instead of rube, no?-->
						in Ariete: facta Solis in Leone.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Opinions on the rock of steel. A saying of the sun in the Ram: a deed of the sun in the Lion.</translation>
		</marginalia>	
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sed tamen erubescat iuris professor arguere, sine vtriusq[ue] iuris artificioso corpore ad
						unguem: cum Belloni Antinomijs: Decij, Dyniq[ue] regulis: Speculatoris, Damasiq[ue]
						regulis magistralibus: Bartholi distinctionibus: Vigelij iure Controuerso:
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Jean Bellon"/>
					<person name="Filippo Decio"/>
					<person name="Dinus de Rossonibus de Mugello"/>
					<person name="Guillaume Durand"/>
					<person name="Guilelmus Damasus"/>
					<person name="Bartolus de Saxoferrato"/>
					<person name="Nicolas Virgil"/> 
					<book title="Antinomiarum iuris dissolutiones"/>
					<book title="Lectura super titulo de regulis iuris"/>
					<book title="De regulis juris"/>
					<book title="Speculum iucidiale"/>
					<book title="Brocarda"/>
					<book title="Distinctiones"/>
					<book title="Methodus juris controversi"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Maranta[e] speculo aureo,
						etiam ad ungue[m].
						Et meus singularis pragmaticus, Durandus: cum =
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Roberto Maranta"/>
					<book title="Speculum aureum"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						= Bertachino semper ad Manum: et pra[e]gnantissimis iam Practicis
						in esse. Mera Legum, Canonum, glossarum puncta, et spicula. intima iuris quinta essentia.					
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Giovanni Bertachini"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>But nevertheless the professor of law is ashamed to argue without having the artificial body of both laws by heart: with Jean Bellon's 'Antinomiarum iuris dissolutiones', with the rules of Filippo Decio and Dinus de Rossonibus de Mugello,
				with the expert rules of Guillaume Durand and Guilelmus Damasus, Bartolus de Saxoferrato's distinctions, Nicolas Virgil's controversial law, Roberto Maranta's 'Speculum aureum', also by heart. And my singular pragmatist, Guillaume
				Durand: always with Giovanni Bertachini at hand. And already with the most pregnant practices in being. The pure points and stings of laws, canons, and glossaries. An inmost quintessence of law.</translation> 
		</marginalia>
		
